        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "ff51ffeabdd90c83",
        "text": "[...] of this book [...] does not need to be rewritten after recent events. But they do make some aspects of contemporary warfare and its limitations clearer than historical analysis has allowed. This is especially true of the idea of the \"war on terror\" as well as the idea of a pax americana, i.e., the unilateral hegemony of a single state, advocated by some members of the Bush administration. From the point of view of the systems-theoretical models used here, such ideas turn out to be neither feasible nor rational. On the contrary, it hardly required seer-like abilities to predict that they would produce paradoxical effects. Indeed, if they were pursued consistently, they could herald the end of the American age. What spoke against this was also foreseeable: The hegemonic ideas propagated by George W. Bush and his comrades-in-arms are not capable of gaining a majority at home in the long term, if only because they are financially unmanageable. All attempts to maintain control over any social system in the long term have always failed in history because of the question of costs.\n"
